03587nam a22004575i 9780773574489DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735744897 a10.1515/97807735744892doi  a(DE-B1597)654504  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD319.P75bB58 2008eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a333.3097171 aBittermann, Rusty, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLady Landlords of Prince Edward Island :bImperial Dreams and the Defence of Property /cMargaret McCallum, Rusty Bittermann. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b20 b&w photos 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Names -- tImperial Land Policy and Women Landlords in Prince Edward Island -- tAnne Saunders, Lady Melville: Managing at Home and Abroad -- tJane Saunders, Lady Westmorland: Perpetual Motion -- tGeorgiana Fane: Defending Position and Property -- tCharlotte Sulivan: The Final Defence -- tDifferences That Matter -- tProprietors’ Estates Purchased by the Prince Edward Island Government, 1875–1880 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1767 decision to divide Prince Edward Island among elite British grantees shaped Island history for more than a century. Lady Landlords of Prince Edward Island examines this history through the lives of four women who, due to the vagaries of family formation and inheritance, became Island landlords. As absentee owners of large estates, each of the four women faced challenges from those who wanted land redistributed in freehold lots to actual settlers. Their individual management strategies were determined in part by class standing and marital status, as well as individual eccentricities and prejudices. Drawing on family and official papers, Rusty Bittermann and Margaret McCallum provide engaging portraits of these women - orphaned heiress, prudent wife and property manager, countess estranged from her husband, independent spinster - as they negotiated relations of power and privilege in a domain dominated by men. Lady Landlords of Prince Edward Island is a compelling narrative that provides a unique perspective on landed society in England in the age of industrialization and reform, making an important contribution to trans-Atlantic, British social, legal, and women's histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aMcCallum, Margaret, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357448940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773574489423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773574489/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles